  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/core_explanation/1",
      "kind": "core_explanation",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "Phonemic Awareness — core idea",
      "content": "Phonemic awareness is the ability to hear, identify, and manipulate individual phonemes — the smallest units of sound in spoken language — without reference to print. A student with phonemic awareness can say that \"cat\" contains three phonemes (/k/ /æ/ /t/), can blend /d/ /ɒ/ /g/ into \"dog\", can delete /k/ from \"cat\" to produce \"at\", and can substitute /b/ for /k/ to produce \"bat\". No letters are involved at any point. Phonemic awareness is the auditory-oral precondition for learning letter-sound correspondence (phonics).",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness.md",
        "startLine": 9,
        "endLine": 40
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/learning_objective/1",
      "kind": "learning_objective",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "Learning Objective",
      "content": "Given any spoken CVC or CCVC word:\n\n(a) the student correctly isolates the initial, medial, and final phonemes;  \n(b) the student correctly counts the phonemes (distinguishing phoneme-count from syllable-count);  \n(c) the student correctly blends three or four spoken phonemes into the target word;  \n(d) the student correctly segments a spoken word into its constituent phonemes in sequence;  \n(e) the student correctly deletes a named phoneme and produces the resulting spoken word;  \n(f) the student correctly substitutes a named phoneme and produces the resulting spoken word.\n\n**Accuracy threshold:** 85% (aligned with mastery_threshold for foundational phonics).\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness.md",
        "startLine": 40,
        "endLine": 55
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/misconception/MC-1",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "— Phonemes Equal Syllables",
      "content": "### MC-1 — Phonemes Equal Syllables\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student claps or taps once per syllable beat when asked to count phonemes; says 'butter' has 2 sounds; says 'happy' has 2 sounds; cannot count more phonemes than syllables in any word.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2 answer = syllable count for a word where syllable-count ≠ phoneme-count; P41 in TA-A01 returns 1 tap for a CVC word.\n\n**Root cause:** Students first learn to clap syllable beats in songs and rhymes. Rhythmic syllable chunking is robust and fires automatically when any counting task involving spoken words is presented. The phoneme concept is less perceptually salient than the syllable for most early learners.\n\n**Repair chain:** TA-C01 — P02→P26→P28→P29→P30→P31→P34→P55→P49|P50→P32\n\n**MAMR status:** Foundational for MC-2. A student who cannot distinguish phonemes from syllables is counting in wrong units entirely. MC-1 must be resolved before MC-2 repair is attempted.\n\n**Resolution signal:** Student correctly counts phonemes (not syllables) in two consecutive novel words from different syllable categories.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness.md",
        "startLine": 5,
        "endLine": 21
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/misconception/MC-2",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "— Phoneme Count Equals Letter Count",
      "content": "### MC-2 — Phoneme Count Equals Letter Count\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student reports 4 phonemes for \"ship\" (counting s-h-i-p); 5 phonemes for \"phone\" (counting p-h-o-n-e); uses letter-counting as default for any phoneme-counting task.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2 answer = 4 for 'fish'; TA-A02 response taxonomy 4-box response for 'ship'.\n\n**Root cause:** Students who know the alphabet apply letter-by-letter counting as a default. The concept that two or more letters can represent one phoneme requires explicit instruction; it is not intuitive from alphabet knowledge alone.\n\n**Repair chain:** TA-C02 — P02→P26→P28→P29→P30→P31→P34→P55→P49|P50→P32 (pre-condition: MC-1 resolved)\n\n**MAMR status:** Dependent on MC-1. Cannot repair before MC-1 is resolved — a student using the wrong counting unit (syllables) cannot benefit from instruction about letters vs. phonemes.\n\n**Resolution signal:** Student correctly counts phonemes (not letters) for a digraph-containing word not used during the repair TA.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-2"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness.md",
        "startLine": 21,
        "endLine": 37
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/misconception/MC-3",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "— Only Initial Phonemes Are Salient",
      "content": "### MC-3 — Only Initial Phonemes Are Salient\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student correctly identifies the first phoneme of any word but says \"I don't know\" or repeats the whole word when asked for the medial or final phoneme.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-1 CORRECT; DB-4 medial follow-up incorrect; P34 for medial position in TA-B01 incorrect.\n\n**Root cause:** The onset (initial consonant) is the most perceptually prominent position in English CVC words. Instructional emphasis on \"what letter does the word START with?\" creates an asymmetry where initial position is treated as the only phonemically relevant position.\n\n**Repair chain:** TA-C03 — P02→P26→P33→P16→P34→P55→P49|P50→P34→P55→P49|P50→P32\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent of MC-1 and MC-2.\n\n**Resolution signal:** Student correctly isolates medial and final phonemes in two consecutive novel CVC words.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-3"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness.md",
        "startLine": 37,
        "endLine": 53
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness/misconception/MC-4",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.phonemic-awareness",
      "title": "— Blending and Segmenting Are the Same Cognitive Skill",
      "content": "### MC-4 — Blending and Segmenting Are the Same Cognitive Skill\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student blends successfully (DB-3 CORRECT) but cannot segment (DB-4 INCORRECT), or vice versa — and is surprised or confused when asked to reverse direction, believing both tasks are identical.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-3 CORRECT + DB-4 INCORRECT (phoneme-to-word direction works; word-to-phoneme fails).\n\n**Root cause:** Both tasks involve phonemes and words, masking their directional difference. Blending is practised earlier and more frequently in typical instruction; segmentation is rarer and therefore not independently proceduralised.\n\n**Repair chain:** TA-C04 — P02→P26→P17→P06→P34→P55→P49|P50→P32\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent of MC-1, MC-2, and MC-3.\n\n**Resolution signal:** Student successfully segments a word they had just blended, and blends a phoneme sequence they had just identified from a segmented word.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-4",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-4"
      ],
